Frankly, I think the modder meme is a little overplayed. I haven't felt an extreme need to mod any of their games. Does the modding work in their favor? Certainly. But it does for most games that allow it. Large scale mods give a lot of legs to games like Paradox games, ARMA, etc. but no-one claims that a company like Paradox relies on mods to make things work for them. Despite Paradox having a history of releasing broken, buggy, and even plain unfinished games. And also selling heaps of overpriced DLC. I'd honestly say a good reason to buy Stellaris is to play the Star Trek mod. It's legit one of the best Star Trek games ever, and it adds stuff that Stellaris itself is sorely missing.

I'm just glad it's there at all. Somehow there has never been a shitstorm about the fact that loads of TES and Fallout mods are highly sexual in nature, and allow you to do some questionable shit. That's the sort of thing that gets the banhammer put on communities, but Bethesda looks at LoversLab, and is like "more customers for us!"

What I think the thing is, is that modders can edit the things Bethesda does in service of mainstream playability. You get mods to eliminate level scaling and such. You get intricate, difficult dungeons, new monsters, etc. But that's not the audience where most of their paycheck comes from.
